$BODY = <<<'HTML'
<p>In recent years, one term has been appearing more and more frequently among those seeking solutions for tinnitus: bimodal neuromodulation. Behind the technical term lies a simple idea and one of the most solid pieces of evidence in recent research.</p>

<h2>How it works: two stimuli, one brain to retrain</h2>
<p>Bimodal neuromodulation combines two synchronised signals: sounds through headphones and gentle electrical pulses from a small device placed on the tongue. Presented together, in a coordinated way, they push the brain to reorganise the overactive auditory circuits at the root of the ringing. It is guided "retraining", not masking.</p>

<h2>What studies show</h2>
<p>In the study published in Science Translational Medicine (Conlon, 2020), in <span class="num">326</span> people the therapy produced a noticeable reduction in tinnitus distress, with <span class="num">80.1%</span> of participants maintaining the improvement at <span class="num">12</span> months after completion. The subsequent study (Conlon, 2022) confirmed reductions of up to <span class="num">20</span> THI points, with <span class="num">91%</span> lasting improvement. These are significant numbers for a field where few things genuinely work.</p>

<h2>What it is NOT</h2>
<p>Bimodal neuromodulation is a medical device (the best known is called Lenire), used with a defined protocol and ideally under the guidance of an audiologist. It is not an app, not a toy and not suitable for everyone. It should be treated as a clinical option, to be evaluated with a specialist, not a purchase to make on your own.</p>

<h2>Where it sits relative to other approaches</h2>
<p>For most people, the path starts with accessible foundations: sound therapy, sleep habits, stress management, cognitive exercises. Bimodal neuromodulation is a more specialised tool, useful when distress is significant and a targeted intervention is sought. An app like AURALIS works on the other side: daily sound, calm and consistency.</p>

<h2>In short</h2>
<p>Bimodal neuromodulation "retrains" the brain with sound and micro-pulses on the tongue, and in the most extensive studies it reduces tinnitus distress with lasting results. It is the most promising approach of recent years, but it remains a medical device used under specialist guidance — an option, not a universal promise.</p>
